A class that parses and stringifies JSON using eval (as implemented in goog.json).
A class that parses and stringifies JSON using the browser's built-in JSON library, if it is available.
Class that is used to serialize JSON objects to a string.
An interface for JSON parsing and serialization.
JSON replacer, as defined in Section 15.12.3 of the ES5 spec.
JSON reviver, as defined in Section 15.12.2 of the ES5 spec.
Tests if a string is an invalid JSON string. This only ensures that we are not using any invalid characters
True if the input is a valid JSON string.

Parses a JSON string and returns the result. This throws an exception if the string is an invalid JSON string.

Note that this is very slow on large strings. Use JSON.parse if possible.
The object generated from the JSON string, or null.
Serializes an object or a value to a JSON string.
A replacer function called for each (key, value) pair that determines how the value should be serialized. By defult, this just returns the value and allows default serialization to kick in.
A JSON string representation of the input.
Sets an error logger to use if there's a recoverable parsing error and goog.json.TRY_NATIVE_JSON is enabled.
The first parameter is the error message, the second is the exception thrown by JSON.parse.

If true, try the native JSON parsing API first. If it fails, log an error and use eval instead. This is useful when transitioning to goog.json.USE_NATIVE_JSON. The error logger needs to be set by goog.json.setErrorLogger. If it is not set then the error is ignored.

If true, use the native JSON parsing API. NOTE: The default goog.json.parse implementation is able to handle invalid JSON. JSPB used to produce invalid JSON which is not the case anymore so this is safe to enable for parsing JSPB. Using native JSON is faster and safer than the default implementation using eval.
